Britannica Web sites
Articles from Britannica encyclopedias for elementary and high school students.Boeing Company - Student Encyclopedia (Ages 11 and up)The Boeing Company is the world’s largest aircraft manufacturer and number one corporate exporter, historically located in Seattle, Washington. The company was founded by William Boeing in 1916 as Pacific Aero Products Company. He also started small airlines to fly mail routes, eventually merging them into what is now United Airlines. (Congress forced separation of aircraft manufacture from airline business in 1934.) Boeing made such well-known war planes as the B-17, the B-47, and the B-25 during World War II, and the B-52 Stratofortress after World War II. Commercial planes include Boeing 707, 727, 747, 757, 767, 777, and 787. Boeing is also active in the U.S. national aerospace program with cruise missile and rocket launchers. (See also aerospace industry).
